label.value: abolished protein sumoylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the sumoylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of meiotic recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Meiotic recombination is a cellular process in which double strand breaks are formed and repaired through a double Holliday junction intermediate, resulting in the equal exchange of genetic material between non-sister chromatids in a pair of homologous chromosomes.

A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of intragenic meiotic recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Intragenic meiotic recombination can result in gene conversion events.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at late replication origin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at late replication origins is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to chromatin at late replication origin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at late replication origins is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the replicative lifespan of a cell population, i.e. the number of divisions cells in the population undergo before death, is lower than normal.

definition.value: Although each cell has a replicative lifespan in that it divides a certain number of times and then dies, replicative lifespan is often measured at the population level, where it is defined by the number of generations at which 50% of the starting cells are dead.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the replicative lifespan of a cell population, i.e. the number of divisions cells in the population undergo before death, is higher than normal.

definition.value: Although each cell has a replicative lifespan in that it divides a certain number of times and then dies, replicative lifespan is often measured at the population level, where it is defined by the number of generations at which 50% of the starting cells are dead.

label.value: normal meiotic DNA double-strand break clipping

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which meiotic DNA double-strand break clipping is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Meiotic DNA double-strand break clipping is the process by which SPO11/Rec12-oligonucleotide complexes are removed from 5' DNA double-strand breaks induced during meiosis.

A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of intergenic meiotic recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Intergenic meiotic recombination reflects crossovers between homologous chromosomes.

label.value: decreased break-induced loss of heterozygosity via chromosomal translocation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosomal translocation that would result in the loss of one of two different alleles of a gene occurs to a lower extent than normal.

definition.value: This phenotype may be observed in diploid cells, or in cells that have two copies of one or more reporter loci but are otherwise haploid. Loss of heterozygosity associated with chromosomal translocation may result from allelic crossover or break-induced replication. In cells with this phenotype, loss of heterozygosity may or may not occur via a different mechanism, such as chromosomal truncation.

label.value: increased break-induced loss of heterozygosity via chromosomal truncation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosomal truncation that would result in the loss of one of two different alleles of a gene occurs to a greater extent than normal.

definition.value: This phenotype may be observed in diploid cells, or in cells that have two copies of one or more reporter loci but are otherwise haploid. Loss of heterozygosity associated with chromosomal translocation may result from allelic crossover or break-induced replication. In cells with this phenotype, loss of heterozygosity may or may not occur via a different mechanism, such as chromosomal truncation.

label.value: normal frequency of break-induced loss of heterozygosity

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosomal truncation that would result in the loss of one of two different alleles of a gene occurs at a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) frequency.

label.value: decreased level of cell cycle regulated gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more cell cycle-regulated mRNAs measured in a cell is lower than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells). Cell cycle-regulated mRNAs are transcribed from genes whose level of transcription varies depending on cell cycle phase.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing potassium chloride.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at highly transcribed RNA polymerase II genes during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin regions where RNA polymerase II actively transcribes genes is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to chromatin at highly transcribed RNA polymerase II genes during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin regions where RNA polymerase II actively transcribes genes is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased nucleosome occupancy at highly transcribed RNA polymerase II genes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleosome occupancy is greater than normal in chromatin regions where RNA polymerase II actively transcribes genes. Nucleosome occupancy measures the tendency for DNA in a given region to be packaged into nucleosomes.

label.value: decreased nucleosome occupancy at highly transcribed RNA polymerase II genes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleosome occupancy is lower than normal in chromatin regions where RNA polymerase II actively transcribes genes. Nucleosome occupancy measures the tendency for DNA in a given region to be packaged into nucleosomes.

label.value: normal nucleosome occupancy at highly transcribed RNA polymerase II genes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleosome occupancy is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in chromatin regions where RNA polymerase II actively transcribes genes. Nucleosome occupancy measures the tendency for DNA in a given region to be packaged into nucleosomes.

label.value: increased duration of mitotic G2 DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the duration of cell cycle arrest or delay due to regulation by the mitotic G2 DNA damage checkpoint is greater than in wild type during a cellular response to ionizing radiation.

label.value: normal histone H2A phosphorylation during cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which histone H2A phosphorylation is normal during a cellular response to ionizing radiation. All histone H2A phosphorylation may be assayed, or phosphorylation of specific sites on histone H2A may be measured.

label.value: increased duration of mitotic cell cycle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of the entire mitotic cell cycle is longer than normal.

definition.value: This term should only be used when the experiment does not distinguish which specific cell cycle phase is longer than normal (for example, if the time from one septation peak to the next is measured).

label.value: abnormal protein dephosphorylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dephosphorylation of one or more specific proteins is abnormal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein dephosphorylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dephosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a lower extent than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dephosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a lower extent than normal during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which a spindle forms with microtubules emanating from three or more poles.
A physical cellular phenotype in which a mitotic spindle forms with microtubules emanating from three or more poles.
A physical cellular phenotype in which a meiotic spindle forms with microtubules emanating from three or more poles.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of sodium ions into a cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of sodium ions into a cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of lithium ions into a cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of lithium ions into a cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of potassium ions into a cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of potassium ions into a cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of sodium chloride than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of magnesium chloride than normal.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing magnesium chloride.
A cellular process phenotype in which proton transport is abnormal.

label.value: decreased proton export during cellular response to glucose stimulus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of proton export is decreased during a cellular response to glucose stimulus.
A phenotype in which a specific transport process is abnormal in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in the mitochondria is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total protein or a specific protein may be measured.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which lithium ion export from the cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: increased rate of mitotic spindle elongation during anaphase B

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of mitotic spindle elongation is increased during anaphase B.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a soluble protein forms prions, by refolding and assembling into highly ordered, self-propagating detergent- and protease-resistant polymers. Phenotypes associated with prions are inherited in a non-Mendelian manner.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which spliced forms of RNAs transcribed from dg repeats in the centromere outer repeat region are present at higher levels than normal.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin filament bundle organization is abnormal. The process normally results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of an actin filament bundle. Actin filament bundles are assemblies of actin filaments organized along a single axis.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the assembly of actin filament bundles is decreased.

label.value: abnormal termination of RNA polymerase I transcription

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of RNA transcription RNA polymerase I from a DNA template is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the export of potassium ions out of a cell is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the export of potassium ions out of a cell occurs to a lower extent than normal.
